The figures also revealed that the number of people in work fell by 43,000 in the latest quarter to March, to 29.7 million, the biggest fall since autumn 2011.

Some 902,000 people had been out of work for more than a year, a 23,000 increase on the three months to December. The number of unemployed 16 to 24-year-olds fell by 17,000 to 958,000.

The government claimed there were now more than half a million job vacancies in the UK, the highest number since 2008.

The number of people claiming out-of-work benefit Jobseekers Allowance in April fell to its lowest level since May 2011, but still stands at 1.52million.

The drop in employment by 43,000 was blamed on a fall in part-time workers and government training schemes.

The number of people in full-time jobs rose by 10,000 on the quarter.

Employment minister Mark Hoban said: 'There are record numbers of women in work, fewer young people unemployed and more vacancies available for those looking for work.

